CSS selectors are used to "find" (or select) the HTML elements we want to style.
Universal Selector (*): Selects all elements on the page.
Type Selector: Selects all elements of a specific type, like div, p, a, etc.
Class Selector (.classname): Selects all elements with a specific class attribute.
ID Selector (#idname): Selects a single element with a specific id attribute.
Descendant Selector (whitespace): Selects an element that is a descendant of another specified element.
Child Selector (>): Selects an element that is a direct child of another specified element.
Adjacent Sibling Selector (+): Selects an element that is directly after another specified element.
General Sibling Selector (~): Selects all elements that are siblings of a specified element.
Attribute Selector ([attribute]): Selects elements based on the presence of a specific attribute.
Attribute Value Selector ([attribute=value]): Selects elements based on the value of a specific attribute.
Attribute Starts With Selector ([attribute^=value]): Selects elements whose attribute value begins with a specified value.
Attribute Ends With Selector ([attribute$=value]): Selects elements whose attribute value ends with a specified value.
*Attribute Contains Selector ([attribute=value])**: Selects elements whose attribute value contains a specified value.
Pseudo-class Selector (e.g., :hover, :first-child): Selects elements based on their state or position in the document.
Pseudo-element Selector (e.g., ::before, ::after): Selects and styles a specific part of an element.
